  "summary": "Colin Lamb discusses potential suspects near the murder scene with Colonel Beck. Lamb identifies Mr. Lyme, an engineer residing at 62 Wilbraham Crescent who travels abroad and has a wife and two sons. Beck compares Lyme's potential cover to a man named Pendleton, who used various wives as disguises. Lamb also mentions MacNorton, a retired Scottish professor at number 63 whose garden adjoins the murder site, and a blind former schoolteacher living alone at number 19. Lamb suggests that the proximity of these gardens would make it easy to dispose of a body and presents Beck with a muddy Czech coin discovered in the back garden of number 19 to support his investigation. Beck teases Lamb about his motives and a girl involved in the case, but Lamb remains focused on his upcoming trip to attend a trial in Crofton.\n\nLater, Lamb visits Whitehall House to see his friend, Hercule Poirot. After being greeted by a servant named George, Lamb enters room 203, where Poirot is sitting by an electric fire with tea and books. Lamb explains that he uses the alias \"Lamb\" to protect his father's identity. The two men discuss the aging process and gardening before transitioning to a conversation about Lamb's father, whom Poirot admires for his unique, trap-setting investigative methods. Poirot concludes the meeting by congratulating Lamb on his recent success with the Larkin case.",
